Title: Putting Semantic-Head-Driven Generation to the Limits: Experiments with multi-purpose semantic representations  
Author: Stephan Busemann 
Address: Stuhlsatzenhausweg 3, 66123 Saarbrucken (Germany)  
Affiliation: German Research Center for Artificial Intelligence (DFKI GmbH)  
Abstract: Constraint-based grammars can, in principle, serve as the major linguistic knowledge source for both parsing and generation. Surface generation starts from input semantics representations that may vary across grammars. For many declarative grammars, the concept of derivation implicitly built in is that of parsing. They may thus not be interpretable by a generation algorithm. We show that linguistically plausible semantic analyses can cause severe problems for semantic-head-driven approaches for generation (shdg). We use SeReal, a variant of shdg and the Disco grammar of German, both developed at DFKI, as our source of examples. We propose a new approach that explicitly accounts for the interface between the grammar and the generation algorithm by adding a control-oriented layer to the linguistic knowledge base that reorganizes the semantics in a way suitable for generation.
